		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Ator’s Druid Law of Safety</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:dragonwine@mindspring.com">Ator of Xegony</a> | 
		            10/4/1999 6:05:02 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Ator&#8217;s Druid Law of Safety<BR>
<BR>
	While I by all means do not consider myself an expert in EQ, I have managed to learn some things that I wanted to pass on to others in hopes of helping you enjoy the game more. These are what I call Ator&#8217;s Laws of Safety for druids. I hope they help you as they have others I have shared them with and taught.<BR>
(1) Always remember green, no experience monsters will kill you faster ganging up on you than one red Mob. So know your targets and be prepared to run like a girly man if necessary. No matter what your level, some mobs like goblins will attack you en masse. While this may be fun for a high level player to see the futility of all these green mobs attacking them, it is NOT fun when you are half-dead and a Hill Giant decides he wants a fresh druid sandwich for lunch. Now you have a hill giant and the rest of your mobs after you and most likely you will be low on mana. So always find out BEFORE you engage any mobs if you can pull one or if they will attack you in swarms. <BR>
(2) Know your spells. By that I mean know how long each buff lasts. I actually put an electric clock on my monitor and timed my spells. A wise man once said, &#8220;Chance favors the prepared mind.&#8221; There is no greater disappointment than engaging a Mob only to have your SoW run out and you get killed. Not only do you lose experience that is so precious and time comsuming to accumulate, but you feel like a real dummy. It only takes a few seconds to take a pen and piece of paper and write down the time you buffed and the time it wears off. Then you will know EXACTLY when you need to buff. When in doubt, buff it! The level 34 spells I currently use I know the exact damage they do and when my buffs wear off. If I am even remotely close to having to buff, I will not engage a mob and let someone else take it than risk losing my experience. For example, the spell regeneration lasts 11 minutes. Skin like steel lasts 36 minutes and bramblecoat last a whopping 1 hour and 45 minutes. So it is the easiest spell to shuffle in and out of your spell line up. I will not go on a rant as I usually do in EQVault&#8217;s Guild Hall page, but the new DoT nerfs are soooo lame. First, Drones of Doom does damage for 90 seconds. Yet to get full advantage of its power you need to either melee the Mob or kill it in 18 seconds which defeats the whole purpose of a 90 second spell to begin with. So you MUST adjust and do not look for your kiting abilities to fully kill a Mob as it once did. Know the exact damage it will do and the time you cast and you will maximize its limited potential. Also know that it does NOT stack. In other words once cast, do not bother to cast a fresh one until some time has run off the clock. Casting two DoT spells back to back is a waste of mana.<BR>
(3) Always med up in camo. Superior Camoflauge is a joke and can be used indoors, but Camoflauge is used by me and other druids I know as it takes less mana and gets the same results. Know that UNDEAD things, skeletons, mummies, etc can see you in camo and will attack you. So if you are hurt and OOM (Out Of Mana) go around other players and ask them to watch out for you while you med. If this is not possible go high up on a zone wall and then camo and med up.Very few mobs will be roaming the top of the zone walls and keep SoW up just in case you need to make a quick exit. <BR>
(4) If you go to another zone you have never been too and are afraid of things attacking you as you run then camo yourself. You cannot interact with other NPC&#8217;s like buying things or giving them items while in camo, but you can safely run in camo and nothing but undead things can see you. Once you get to level 24 and get wolf form your sanctions are lowered and aggro (aggressive animals) will be less likely to attack you. In spite of what Verant tells you aggro animals WILL attack you as a druid while you are medding up. I have even had Splitpaw Gnolls and lionesses attack me at level 32 while medding at the Lake Rathe zone in druid form. So remember go camo until level 24 and they cannot disturb your meditation.<BR>
(5) Do research and know at all times where the zones are located. I cannot tell you how many times things have gone horribly wrong and I have had to zone to stay alive. DO NOT depend on your group to keep you alive either, as they may die as well. Before ANY group engages in fighting they ALL should know where the zones are located in case you have to make a quick exit. In heavily populated zones I have been in groups where the lag was so bad, by the time you cast healing on a member about to die, they were gone. So be prepared to save yourself and others by knowing where safety can easily be reached. <BR>
(6) This last one is SO IMPORTANT I have saved it for last. If you NEVER remember any of the other things I have shared with you remember this one. Whatever you were fighting when you leveled CONTINUE to fight the same thing until you get a minimum of one bubble of experience before moving on to other places. I call this my &#8220;insurance bubble.&#8221; It is vitally important to do this especially at your new spell levels because if you die and get taken back to your old level, you CANNOT use your new spells until you re-level. Even though they are scribed and in your spell book, you will get a message that tells you that you are unable to use this level of spell. So if you have your insurance bubble and die, your spells are still intact and you are able to use them. Very, very important as when going to fight a mob nothing is worse than finding out all your new spells cannot be used with the Mob bearing down on you with death and destruction on its warped little mind.  And the new spells are no longer in your memmed spell portion. <BR>
I hope these will help you and there are many more but these are the best ones to remember. Good luck my brother and sister druid.<BR>
Yours in Honor,<BR>
Ator of Xegony <BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
